listing_title: The ultimate laid-back house in an extremely convenient location!
listing_description:
This 4-bedroom, 2-bathroom, 2-car garage house in Harrison unquestionably enjoys the most advantageous location. Not only are buses 18, 21, and 22 located just in front of the house, but the Nullarbor Avenue light rail station is only a 10-minute walk away. Furthermore, the suburb surrounding the house is well-planned and includes a variety of easily accessible restaurants, bakeries, schools, parks, etc. The most famous Mullion Park in Harrison is about 300 meters from your house. Thus, you may experience the utmost ease while also having more options for leisurely relaxation.

The entire house is designed as a double living room, with a versatile and roomy living area at the entrance connected to the other living room by an open kitchen. Next to the second living room, the floor-to-ceiling windows that connect to the Japanese garden make the house exceptionally bright and airy. After traversing two living rooms and a kitchen, we will reach a rather private area in the house's backside. Three single rooms and a very spacious master bedroom provide tenants with plenty of space and possibilities. There is not just a bathroom but also a separate cloakroom in the master suite, making it quite roomy and cozy to live here.

Features:
-	Tesla charging post
-	Cozy garden with high privacy and rustic style
-	Bright and spacious interior
-       Separate cloakroom for master bedroom
-	Range hoods and flooring and curtains have been recently renovated throughout the house
-	Bathroom appliances like taps and shower roses have been renovated
-	Partially furnished
-	separate living areas, gas cooktop, ducted reverse cycle air conditioning
-	Excellent location, close to LRT, schools and supermarkets, bus stop in front of city

This home is indulged by a particular quality of light and generosity of space. Large timber windows frame garden views and an overarching mood of joy. This charming, three-bedroom cottage sits comfortably within a large and enveloping garden, on a quiet Eucalypt lined street. Period details sit perfectly alongside a crisp white palette, as the garden's fragrance breezes in. The enormous sunny and magic block brims with potential* and comfort simultaneously. A place where childhood memories are created. With backyard cricket, warm spring evenings, and the birth of DIY projects, providing the quintessential Australian home. 
 
High ceilings, ornate cornices, wooden panelling and sectioned timber windows create a wonderful sense of romance and charisma. Light timber floors flow underfoot, art sings on the white walls and select modern and vintage pieces, combine with ease. 
 
The north facing living area enjoys sumptuous garden views, via banks of timber windows and flows to an intimate dining nook. The kitchen is accented with vintage linoleum flooring and cabinetry in a shade of soft blush. 
 
All three bedrooms frame leafy views and centre around the original bathroom and separate toilet. The large master bedroom has ample built-in storage and vista to a towering gum. 
 
To the rear of the home a sunroom provides a sequestered second living space - the perfect nook for afternoon tea or a glass as the sun sets. Deep within the rear garden, there is a secret room that could easily be utilised as an artist studio, writing niche or guest room.  
 
Retro-fitted double glazing and added insulation enhances this warm and likeable home. Also of note is the large laundry with second shower and the double garage.
 
Camelias, olive trees, border hedging and generous lawns imbue the garden with a sense of nostalgia. An Italian legacy has been left by the home's former residents. Vegetable gardens, scaffolding for grapevines, under house cellar, and a plethora of tomatoes is easy to imagine on this sunny, fertile plot.

listing_title: 4 Bedroom Family Home with Spacious Backyard
listing_description:

The kitchen which is done in modern tones, boasts plenty of cupboard space, benchtop prep space, dishwasher, and expansive views of the rear garden.

Off the kitchen is a separate dining area with a glass sliding door to the rear covered balcony entertaining space. Wrapping around the other side of the kitchen is a large lounge room and family room offering complete flexibility to suit various situations.

Sensor lights line the hallway heading towards the 4 sizable bedrooms, most with built in robes. The main bedroom has more than enough room to fit a king sized bed and is complete with its own ensuite.

This beautiful home is close to schools, shops, and transport and is a short walk away from Mount Taylor which offers plenty of walking trails and exquisite views of Canberra and beyond.

Suburb Snapshot 
Watson was named after the Honourable John Christian Watson  1867-1941 . Honourable John Christian Watson was the third Prime Minister of the Commonwealth and first Labour Prime Minister from April - August 1904. He became prominent in Labour movement in 1893 when he was elected as the President of the Sydney Trades and Labour Council at the age of twenty-six. He was also elected to Federal Parliament in 1901 and appointed leader of the Labour Party. He retired in 1910. Streets in Watson are named after judges.

Suburb Snapshot 
Downer is a suburb of Canberra, Australia, in the city's inner north. The suburb is bounded by Northbourne Avenue, Antill Street and Philip Avenue. 

The suburb was gazetted in 1960 and named after Sir John Downer  1844 1915  Premier of South Australia and a member of the first Australian Senate in 1901. There is no specific theme for street names. 

The buildings which make up the Downer community centre and former shops, were built for the CSIRO in 1930s, and the area now comprising Downer was an agricultural research facility for the CSIRO. The area now comprising the suburb was used between 1939 45 as a plantation for the growth of opium poppy to provide a source for medications in the unavailability of imported supplies. The large pine and gum trees which surround the block around the shops were planted in this time as a wind break for the CSIRO building. Large trees  Camden Woolybutts  along Swinden street were also planted then, as Swinden street was the driveway for the CSIRO building, where it connected to Northbourne Avenue.

Suburb Snapshot
Crace is a suburb of Canberra, Australia in the district of Gungahlin. It was named after Edward Kendall Crace an original settler in the Gungahlin area. Streets in Crace are named after parishes and land divisions from colonial times.  It is bounded by the Barton Highway, Gundaroo Drive, Nudurr Drive and Gungahlin Drive. Located in the suburb is the Canberra Nature Park of Gungaderra Grasslands nature reserve. At the 2016 census, it had a population of 4,459.
The suburb is under construction, with more than half of the houses completed as of July 2012. Road construction commenced in July 2008. The construction of 21 display homes was completed in May 2009.
The ACT government has selected developers for the area as Defence Housing Australia and Canberra Investment Corporation. Expectations are that there will be 1200 houses built over the next six years. The developers are expected to make  60,000,000 but have to share half that with the government. Some very small blocks will be released for low cost housing with 85  released for high cost housing. Eventually the suburb will have 1500 houses on 140 hectares.

Suburb Snapshot
Curtin is named after John Curtin, Australian Prime Minister between 1941 and 1945. Its streets are named after state premiers.

Curtin shopping centre offers the following services: Coles supermarket, post office, newsagent, bank, real estate agent, chemist, hairdresser, barber, travel agent, optometrist, florist, bakery, greengrocer and numerous cafes and coffee shops. Of note is the Curtin Milk Bar which was the longest running cafe in the area. Its style and operation remained unchanged since the 1970s until its closure in December 2017. Nearby is Curtin Scout Hall.

The suburb celebrated the fiftieth anniversary of the arrival of its first residents in 2014. As part of that celebration, the Canberra   District Historical Society, which is headquartered at the shops, helped local residents to record oral histories of their memories. They can be accessed on a Web site called Curtin Living Memories. Residents subsequently compiled and published a book on life in the suburb called, Curtin Turns 50.

This sleek contemporary-designed 3-bedroom townhouse offers an open-plan living space flooding the area with natural light. Boasting high ceilings, double-glazed windows and full-height bi-fold doors off the living area that effortlessly extend onto a large covered balcony with stunning views, it makes the perfect spot to extend your living space.  The beautifully appointed kitchen features overhead dark cabinetry, subway tiles, pendant lights, an integrated dishwasher, gas cooktop and soft close drawers, creating a modern industrial feel. Floating timber floors throughout the living space are easy to care for and add a warm ambiance to the space.  The separate lounge is carpeted and is also on this level.

Upstairs, all 3 bedrooms have generously sized built-in robes for added storage with the master suite offering an ensuite. The cleverly designed additional 2 bathrooms, one located on the upper level and on the lower level showcasing herringbone tiling, floating vanities, mat black tapware and a bathtub in the main bathroom. Ducted reverse cycle air conditioning ensures your year-round comfort and a private rear courtyard perfect for entertaining and a double garage takes care of your car accommodation.

Denman Prospect is Molonglo's newest suburb. Less than 15 minutes from the city, Denman Prospect offers proximity to nearby employment hubs in the City, Belconnen, and Woden. Local supermarket, a gymnasium, and coffee shops already established directly below and the ease of public transport right at your doorstep. This property has the added bonus of your electricity and gas costs being included in your rent.

3 bedroom 2 storey townhouse

listing_title: You've got to go to Gow!
listing_description:
On one of Ainslie's shortest and lesser-known streets, in an elevated and fabulous location, you'll find this extended, privately built home. It's at the city end of the suburb and very close to Mt Ainslie with easy access to its magic nature reserve. If you're into bushwalking or mountain biking, you're going to love this position. On the other hand, if eating and drinking is more your thing, you've got easy access to the delights of Braddon and the Canberra CBD.

It's only when you climb the steps to the front door of the home and turn to face the city that you realise just how elevated this position is, with picturesque views to Black Mountain tower and the CBD. The home itself is some 193m2 of living with both front and rear decks and a generous garage underneath. The first thing that you'll notice upon entry are the rich and warm polished Ash floorboards which stretch from the generous entry through the large lounge and dining room. Polished concrete floors add a contemporary feel to part of the extension. There is a family room off the kitchen which opens through lovely cedar doors onto the rear deck and overlooks the in-ground pool, but I think that it will be the sunny lounge and dining room where you will do most of your living. This spacious room also opens out onto the deck and features a lovely outlook to Mt Ainslie. There are 4 bedrooms in all  all with built in robes  although the current owner has utilized one for her private business and this room has its own external access.

Both bathrooms and the kitchen were renovated in 2006 and the second bathroom has a large shower and underfloor heating. There's ducted gas heating as well as reverse-cycle air conditioning for year-round comfort. The back yard is surrounded by a high hedge, making the pool super private, yet still sunny. The tandem garage has an automatic door and contains a safe and three phase power - ready for the addition of a car charger. There's a circular driveway which is so very useful for easy access and extra off-street parking. The current owner has already downsized and is committed to a sale.

At a glance;
  Privately built home with 193m2 of living.
  Elevated location with views to Black Mountain and Mt Ainslie, and city glimpses.
  Extension and renovations by renowned architect Anna Pender
  766m2 block with private and established rear garden.
  Front and rear hardwood decks
  In-ground pool
  Moments from Mt Ainslie nature reserve
  3-minute drive to Ainslie shops
  5-minute drive to Canberra CBD

Facts:
Availability: Now!
Pets: Tenant's to seek consent from Landlord
Lease Period: 12 months - ending November 2023
Parking: Garage 
Cooking: Gas cooking
EER: 2.5

listing_title: Why Rent a unit when you can have this awesome Courtyard Home-with extra energy saving benefits!!
listing_description:
This courtyard house is quite the package… It has so many features including large solar system!!

Welcome to this great 3 -bedroom home located in the popular "The Fair" complex in the suburb of Watson, and only a short drive to the bustling Watson shopping centre, the Dickson shopping and restaurant precinct with a myriad of shops, restaurants, bars, cafes and supermarkets with the new Coles supermarket well underway.

The property provides a low maintenance rear garden suitable for families or young couples, several vegetable pods in the rear courtyard, some with vegetables and herbs great for the cook of the family and a lemon, lime and 2 feijoa trees all fruiting. An additional outdoor space is the deck located off the living/kitchen area, perfect for your morning coffee.

A well-appointed modern kitchen with electric cooking, Bosch stainless steel dishwasher, plenty of bench and storage options. Three spacious bedroom all with built in robes with the main having mirrored robes, the bathroom comes complete with bathtub, separate shower and vanity and there is also a separate toilet and handbasin located adjacent off the entry.

A huge bonus and energy saving for a young family is the PV (photovoltaic) system is 5.61 kwh and the battery is 13.8 kWh. During the summer the peak production is about 35-40 kwh per day, in the winter it can be as low as 6-8 kwh per day on a rainy overcast day. During the summer with moderate usage as a family of 4 you may not need to pay for electricity bill at all, instead you can earn credits to your accounts by selling back to the grid. With the surging price in energy, the combination of solar system and battery like this will save you heaps of money and no need to wait for the off-peak hours to use the appliances.
The hot water is also heated by a passive solar panel, so that will not require any extra electricity during the summer but may need to be boosted with electricity during the winter.
Overall if you are strategic in usage the extra electricity that you sell back to the grid during the summer months will balance out with the extra grid electricity you use during the winter months. 

At a glance;

• A good size large living space with lots of natural light, wide halls, storage, lock up garage
• Large master bedroom, would fit a king size bed ,3-door mirrored wardrobe and lots of shelves
• Second room is queen size with double built in wardrobe
 * Daikin RC wall mounted system in lounge room with electric heating in hallway
• The bathroom is well appointed with a separate shower and bathtub
• Laundry is located in the garage
• A modern kitchen featuring electric cooking and dishwasher
• Low maintenance gardens front & rear, including established vegetable pods
• Large Solar System as detailed above-wonderful energy saving features

Location? It couldn’t get any better! Some of the reasons why location is ideal:

• Located in the newer part of Watson
• 7 km to the CBD & Braddon
• Few minutes away from Dickson restaurants and shopping
* Easy access to major arterial roads such as the Federal Highway easy access heading to Sydney
* Walking distance to the very popular Epic Farmers Markets & Showground
• 15-minute drive to the airport
• Minutes away from Mount Majura nature reserve, ideal for walking, hiking or bike riding
• EER not available for this property

Please note-Pets may be considered upon application will need to be approved by owner and processed through the body corporate.

Weekly Rent $650
Rent is payable Fortnightly or per Calendar monthly basis 
Formula – Weekly rent divided by 7 days x 365 divided x 12
Calendar monthly rent is payable by direct debit

Suburb Snapshot 
Belconnen is the most inner suburb of the larger district of Belconnen in Canberra, Australia. Sharing its name with the larger district which encapsulates it, the suburb is surrounded with well developed infrastructure, and planning which allows it sunset  views from the Brindabellas on its western side. The suburb contains important amenities for the District of Belconnen including the Belconnen Town Centre and Lake Ginninderra as well as its own well populated residential areas. It is bounded by Ginninderra Drive, Aikman Drive, Eastern Valley Way, Belconnen Way and Coulter Drive. It has a number of parks such as Margaret Timpson Park,  within the town centre  Eastern Valley Oval,  on the lower slope of Emu Ridge  and on the foreshores of Lake Ginninderra, Diddams Close Park and John Knight Memorial Park. 

The name Belconnen has been associated with the district since the days of the early settlers. In the city of Canberra, suburbs are assigned street names that reflect a distinct sub-group of cultural or historical Australian significance. The streets in the suburb of Belconnen are named for Lord Mayors and Mayors.

Suburb Snapshot
Named for William James Farrer, who was a wheat-breeding pioneer, many of whose experiments were conducted at Lambrigg near Tharwa. The suburb's streets are named after agriculturalists, with the exception of Lambrigg Street, which was the name of Farrer's property in Tharwa.

The Farrer Ridge Nature Reserve, part of the Canberra Nature Park and the southern limit of the suburb, provides for bushwalking and stunning vistas.

The suburb is one of the oldest suburbs in Canberra, a relatively young city, settled in 1922 and gazetted as a division name in September 1928. It contained Canberra's first light-industrial area. The kitchen includes Caesar stone benchtops, AEG top of the range appliances and the ceramic cooktop provides a functional and easy to maintain kitchen.
 
The main bedroom is generous in size and complete with walk in wardrobe as well as a large ensuite and sliding doors to the rear yard leading to a small porch area. Bedrooms 2 and 3 are good size rooms with built in robes. Bedroom 4 is located at the front of the house which could also be used as a home office. All the bedrooms are carpeted while the rest of the home is tiled timber look tiles.
 
The main bathroom has a separate bath and shower, and the hallway has a multitude of storage options. Suburb Snapshot
Phillip is a suburb of Canberra, Australia in the district of Woden Valley. It is located in the centre of the district and contains the district's main commercial centre, Woden Town Centre. The suburb is named after Arthur Phillip, the first Governor of New South Wales. The suburb name was gazetted on 12 May 1966. Streets in Phillip use names associated with the First, Second and Third Fleets; streets in the Swinger Hill were named after architects.

Phillip also contains a number of sporting facilities, including the Phillip Enclosed Oval, which has been known as Football Park since 1981 and was the headquarters of Australian rules football in Canberra during the 1980s and 1990s, and the Phillip Swimming   Ice Skating Centre, home to the CBR Brave of the Australian Ice Hockey League.

This unit features an oversized bedroom, full size kitchen overlooking a large living space with separate access via a side gate to the main house. The kitchen offers plenty of bench space and storage, opening out to a large living area with sweeping views of the Arboretum and Black Mountain tower. 

This is the perfect unit for a young professional looking for a convenient, low maintenance lifestyle at a great price.

listing_title: Contemporary Family Living with a Prestigious Location
listing_description:
Located in one of the most sought-after streets in the neighborhood, preferred for its elevation, sits this north facing contemporary residence is aesthetically stunning and functionally brilliant. Just a stone throws away from the Evelyn Scott School (pre-school to year 10). Walking distance from Ridgeline park (One of the best playgrounds in Canberra). 100 meters away from bus stop. This 373 sqm, 4 bedrooms and 3 bathrooms luxury home designed by renowned Canberra Architect Tomi Milin is distinguished by its innovative contemporary design which is sitting beautifully on the block, perfectly oriented with panoramic vistas.

This home is designed on an impressive scale and provides wonderful light-filled spaces catering for every scenario and a growing family. The home is brimming with high quality fixtures and fittings and the expansive layout is highlighted with beautiful flooring. Perfectly oriented to the north, open plan kitchen and living region seamlessly leading to an outdoor alfresco and balcony each side with high sliders. A designer kitchen is emphasized with an expansive stone kitchen island bench and walk in pantry and high end Frankie appliances.
The functional floor plan comprises four extra-large bedrooms most with its own en-suite, five separate living spaces including outdoor living/ entertaining areas with gas BBQ points, ensuring ample space for family living comfort. The rear garden is beautifully established to create a tranquil environment and has grass area for kids to play and space to grow your own fresh produce.

Following a grand outdoor entrance, upstairs comes the stylish lounge room opening out to an outdoor living, family living and dining area are adjacent to wide balcony with soaring northern sunlight and spectacular views of mountains, telstra tower and even Australian parliament. The fourth private room on this level has an en-suite and built in robe. This room offers fabulous versatility and can easily be used as a games room, or home office. Two more of the home's five generous bedrooms are also on this level and are serviced well by a quality finished bathroom and separate powder room.

Impressive in its proportions the beautiful master suite provides an urban retreat nicely placed at rear with WIR and double vanities in en-suite.

Features include:

- Square-set finish with all windows
- Panoramic views from the house, balcony and alfresco
- Master Bedroom with walk in wardrobe & built in robe
- All other bedrooms are generously sized & feature built-in robes
- Multiple Living areas
- Large family & meals area
- North facing living areas
- All windows Double glazed
- Separate dual living or teenager retreat with its own kitchen and rumpus downstairs
- Bathroom with bathtub
- Built in cabinetry in wardrobes
- Separate laundry with ample storage
- Large Covered, Outdoor entertaining area
- 6Kw Solar panels
- Walking distance to shops, transportation and schools
- EER 6.0
- Available now

Suburb Snapshot
Civic is the name by which the central business district of Canberra is commonly known. It is also called Civic Centre, City Centre, Canberra City and Canberra, but its official division name is City.

Canberra's City was established in 1927, although the division name City was not gazetted until 20 September 1928. Walter Burley Griffin's design for Canberra included a "Civic Centre" with a separate "Market Centre" located at what is now Russell. However Prime Minister Stanley Bruce vetoed this idea and only the Civic Centre was developed; the idea of the Market Centre was abandoned.

This is not just any apartment, this is 'The Griffin'! Offering timber flooring to all living areas, under-tile heating to all bathrooms, ducted heating and cooling, externally ducted rangehood, feature glass cabinetry and luxurious 30mm stone benchtop are all standard.

Additional amenities include a Wellness Centre incorporating a 25m indoor lap pool, steam room and sauna and uniquely segregated weights and cardio gyms. - Floor to ceiling double glazed windows
- Fully ducted reverse cycle heating and cooling
- Quality engineered timber floors
- Fibre optic broadband
- Video intercom system for visitors
- Direct pedestrian and bicycle access to Lake Burley Griffin

Suburb Snapshot
Lawson is a suburb in the Belconnen district of Canberra, located within the Australian Capital Territory, Australia. It does not have any suburban houses, consisting only of part of Lake Ginninderra, the Belconnen Naval Transmission Station, and an open area of grassland where there is a reservoir and substation. A bicycle path runs alongside Ginninderra Drive, another along the shore of the lake. The area is surrounded by Baldwin Drive, William Slim Drive and Ginninderra Drive. It lies next to the suburbs of McKellar, Giralang, Kaleen, Bruce and Belconnen.

The suburb derives its name from Henry Lawson, short story writer and poet. The streets in Lawson are named after aspects of Australia appearing in his writing.

Suburb Snapshot
The District of Gungahlin is one of the original eighteen districts of the Australian Capital Territory used in land administration. The district is subdivided into divisions  suburbs , sections and blocks. Gungahlin is an Aboriginal word meaning either "white man's house" or "little rocky hill".

Within the district is Canberra's northernmost town centre that is situated 10 kilometres  6.2 mi  north of Canberra city centre. The town centre is one of five satellites of Canberra, seated in Woden, Tuggeranong, Weston Creek and Belconnen.
The traditional custodians of the district are the indigenous people of the Ngunnawal tribe.

Ngunnawal is a suburb in the district of Gungahlin in Canberra, Australia. The suburb is named in tribute to the Ngunnawal people, the original inhabitants of the area. This unique and cutting-edge three-bedroom apartment is set in a boutique development in Canberra's sought-after inner north suburb of Turner. 

This property is being offered fully furnished and equipped – all you need to bring is your belongings and linen. 

Located close to the city with its offices, restaurants and shopping areas, this modern and spacious apartment is also within walking distance to the Australian National University and surrounded by beautiful tree-lined streets and open spaces. 

Exuding style and quality throughout, the open floor plan living areas take full advantage of the relaxing treetop views, with floor to ceiling windows.  

Leading off the living areas through glass sliding doors is a large balcony with outdoor bar, extending the living area and providing the perfect spot to entertain. 

The same level features a large main bedroom, second balcony, walk-in wardrobe with excellent storage space, and ensuite. 

The galley-style kitchen, which is the central hub of the apartment, boasts caesarstone bench tops, Bosch stainless steel appliances, an in-sinkerator and glass splash back. On the same level is a laundry with adjoining powder room. 

The remaining two bedrooms, which are on the third level, have views of Black Mountain and Mount Ainslie, and built-in robes. One features a queen bed and desk – perfect for working from home. The other bedroom has a king single bed. The second bathroom features a bath. 

High quality finishes throughout the apartment include reverse cycle air conditioning in all rooms and double-glazed windows. Scandinavian style furniture adds to the warmth of the apartment. 
 
There is secure side-by-side parking for two cars in the basement, with a large storage cage. The complex also offers a shared rear yard with a veggie garden and grassed area.

Suburb Snapshot 
Braddon is a Canberran suburb located next to Civic. Gazetted in 1928, the suburb was initially established as a division and was the location of Canberra's first light industrial district. It was named after Sir Edward Nicholas Coventry Braddon, an Australian politician who was one of the authors of the Australian constitution.

Today, Braddon boasts a vibrant community that has evolved from a sleepy, semi-urban precinct where industrial companies and offices are headquartered to a coveted lifestyle district that knows no rest. Those in the know are aware that Braddon is top of mind when it comes to its gastronomic surprises and that Braddon residents themselves are spoilt for choice. From ethnic dishes to home-cooked fare, Braddon, Canberra restaurants surely have something for everyone.

Suburb Snapshot
Palmerston is a suburb in the Canberra, Australia district of Gungahlin. The postcode is 2913. The suburb is named after George Thomas Palmer  1784 1854  who established a settlement in the Canberra region in 1826 called Palmerville, which was later renamed Ginninderra. It was gazetted on 20 March 1991. Streets are named after mountains and mountain ranges of Australia, with the main street called Kosciuszko Avenue. It is next to the suburbs of Nicholls, Gungahlin, Crace and Franklin. It was the second suburb to be developed in the Gungahlin district, after the industrial suburb of Mitchell. It is bounded by Gungahlin drive and Gundaroo drive.

Palmerston is mainly a residential area with a mix of single homes and duplexes. At the centre of the suburb there are small medical, shopping and community centres. 
Palmerston Primary School opened in 1994 and a large neighbourhood oval is adjacent to the school. A number of cyclepaths cross the suburb, with pedestrian and cycle underpasses at several road crossings. Fruit trees, including plums and apples are scattered along the public thoroughfares of Palmerston. 

Palmerston is underlaid by the Canberra Formation from the late middle Silurian age. The area was studied in more detail than many other parts of Canberra by J P Ceplecha from the ANU in 1971.

Mostly the Canberra Formation is slaty shale and mudstone. A layer of ashstone has been folded to form 75 meter wide exposures on the surface. These are in the shape of an ear of corn with the major axis pointing north north east. The major axis is determined by an anticline. A syncline determines the western side of the ashstone, with an anticline further to the west. A triangle of siltstone has been lifted up by faults into the western corner of Palmerston. A long fault aligned with the folds follows along the east side of Ginninderra Creek. The Winslade Fault comes in from the south heads north and joins up with the above long fault. The Gungahlin fault also parallels the folds and cuts through the east side of Palmerston. It forms the eastern limit of the ashstone.

Ainslie is a leafy suburb of Canberra, Australia in the North Canberra district. The suburb is bounded by Limestone Avenue and Majura Avenue to the west and north, Phillip Avenue to the north-east, Mount Ainslie to the east and Quick Street to the south.

The suburb is characterised by leafy streets, and mainly by detached single dwelling houses. Many see a "village" atmosphere around the many small parks.

listing_title: Beautiful apartment home with gorgeous garden - house style living
listing_description:
Minutes to The Kingston shops - the Foreshore and Lake Burley Griffin  

 This Heritage listed home known as "Whitley House" was designed by the celebrated architect Cuthbert Whitley in 1939. He was a leading exponent of the radical inter-war functionalist style that came to Canberra in 1939. The Whitley Houses located in both Griffith and Braddon are listed on the ACT Chapter of the Australian Institute of Architects) Register of Significant Twentieth Century Architecture. The houses are regarded by the RAIA as being excellent examples of the inter–war functionalist style and are some of the first functionalist houses in Australia designed and built by government.

 Unit 1 of 3 Burke Crescent Griffith offers the lovely architecture of the period but with modern interiors in keeping with the history of the building.  More like a separate home than an apartment this property has an individual separate entrance and a garden space usually only seen in freestanding homes. 

The interiors are light filled and modern but keeping with the charm of the heritage listed building. All on one level this apartment opens into a large combined kitchen - dining and living area with views out to the garden from the large windows. With stylish parquetry flooring this area is a great hub of the home. 

The large kitchen with an oversized island bench space has an AEG oven and Miele induction cooktop along with great storage space. Adjacent to the living area is a stylish study nook complete with glass French doors and a view to the garden. 

The 2nd and 3rd bedrooms are segregated from the main bedroom and both are of a good size with ample wardrobe space and good sized windows. 

The master bedroom is a great size - with plenty of room for a king sized bed- and separated from the ensuite via stylish plantation shutters. The ensuite is oversized with deep bath as well as a good sized shower and vanity. There is also a spacious WIR with sliding door. 

The main bathroom has a bath with combined shower to service the other two bedrooms. 

This gorgeous apartment not only has lovely interiors but has a large fully fenced garden which any home owner would be proud of!  Totally unexpected in apartment living and offering a really great area for entertaining or ample space for the children to play.  

With Kingston & Manuka only blocks away you can stroll to your favourite coffee shop or restaurant, cycle to the lake and you are minutes away from the Parliamentary triangle. Conveniently located close to transport, shopping & the picturesque Kingston Foreshore precinct, this inner south location offers a lifestyle that's hard to beat. Eyre Street markets are just up the road and the ovals down the block. 

Features include:

* Beautiful landscaped garden - fully fenced and private
* Living area 153m2 approx
^ Near new carpeting and freshly painted throughout

Nature is all around yet just a short walk away is the Chifley shops and recreation area, and it's only a short drive to the Phillip commercial precinct and retail stores, restaurants and cafés of the Woden Town Centre.

The home, which sits on a large 944m² block, has a very warm ambience, with lots of windows which take in the greenery in the leafy garden and the reserve beyond and fills the interior spaces with natural light. There are three bedrooms with built-in wardrobes - the main bedroom's ensuite, family bathroom and separate toilet have been renovated. The spacious living areas include the lounge room, formal dining room and meals area off the kitchen, which has also been tastefully updated. The home's living space has been supplemented with the addition of a lovely sunroom extension with floor-to-ceiling glass and practical tiled floor – the perfect spot to sit and relax while enjoying the peacefulness of this ideal location.

The back yard is a great size for children to enjoy playing in a secure space and includes an additional double garage.

Recently repainted, re-carpeted and with new window treatments throughout, its in as new condition and features 2 spacious sundrenched living areas and a beautiful kitchen complete with island bench, stone bench tops and stainless steel appliances.

The huge segregated main bedroom boasts a large ensuite bathroom complete with custom built double bowl vanity, a big walk in robe and it also enjoys peaceful water views.

listing_title: Unrivalled Quality, Location and Unique Style
listing_description:
This luxury townhouse was meticulously planned inside & out, Unit 7 really is an exclusive blend of style, location, & design.   

The home's distinctly stunning interior comprises four bedrooms, 1 bathroom & 2 ensuites. One of the bedrooms & ensuites is located on the ground floor, meaning you could comfortably live on the ground floor. The front & back courtyard has been crafted with curved Corten edging which creates an industrial yet elegant feel & pair well with the French pattern travertine pavers.  

The kitchen features two sets of twin cone downlights to the kitchen workbench & LED downlights to the cooking area, this space is filled with not only natural light but as with the remainder of the home benefits from incredible custom lighting.  The attention to detail & style is further emphasised with Grey Ironbark wooden strips fitted to the front of the beautiful kitchen bench.   

The Siemens appliances add sophistication & simplicity complemented with two ovens & a plate warmer, the top oven is both a smart & steam oven & the bottom has use as a microwave & smart oven. Both ovens are fitted with meat thermometers which stop cooking once the meat is ready, ensuring the perfect roast!  You'll even be impressed with the whisper-quiet dishwasher & its incredible features- projecting the status of the cycle on the floor via LED lights! A special feature that is included in the sale is the top-of-the-range Liebherr side-by-side fridge/freezer & wine fridge.  
  
All bedrooms are quality sized & include built-in wardrobes & are complimented with Aeratron DC Fans & sheer curtains delivering enough light throughout the day & keep the warmth in on those cooler days. The upstairs bedrooms feature carpet & the downstairs bedroom features ceramic tiles that look like floorboards & in winter allow the highly efficient hydronic heating to ooze natural warmth into the house & your bare feet. The bathrooms have been designed to stand out with their immaculate colours & natural warm textured wall tiles. 


Property Features Include:

- 2-storey design 
- Open plan living & dining on ground floor
- Two private courtyards   
- Ensuite on ground level 
- Grey Ironbark Timber stairs/handrails and balustrades 
- Aeratron DC Fans in all four bedrooms and a larger single fan in lounge.   
- Hydronic heating  
- Siemens ovens and plate warmer

- Siemens whisper quiet integrated dishwasher  
- Liebherr side by side fridge/freezer/wine fridge.  
- Top quality German "Markilux MX3" remotely operated awning with motion sensor

- Double glazed & argon-filled windows & sliding doors

You now have your chance to make this brand new townhouse, your new home. This established area is known for its leafy streets, great food and a thriving cultural scene. Locals enjoy a village atmosphere and a true sense of community.

As you walk into the property, you're greeted with high ceilings, quality finishes & beautiful timber flooring. In the kitchen, BOSCH appliances & stone benchtops will make cooking enjoyable for anyone, from your amatuer cook to your budding chef. 

The intelligently thought-out design will provide you with a downstairs bathroom & multi-purpose area upstairs fit to be your home office or the kids games area. 

The 3 spacious bedrooms are fitted with full height windows, displaying amazing views of the complex & surroundings. Two bedrooms come with built-in robes, while the main bedroom boasts a walk-in wardrobe & private ensuite with a double vanity. You will be pleased with ducted air conditioning & heating system to the whole townhouse for year round comfort. 

Features include:

- 3 bedrooms with built-in/walk-in robes
- Machined timber flooring
- Private courtyard & balcony
- Double vanity in ensuite
- Lockable double garage
- Double glazed windows
- Bosch kitchen appliances
- Ducted heating & cooling
- Washer & dryer combo
- Development Gym
- Outdoor dining & BBQ area
- EER 6.0

Available Now


The Village Green is the heart of Kiara-a landscaped open space that runs through the centre of the development, allowing sight-lines to Black Mountain to the north and pedestrian access to Jerrabomberra Sports Ground to the south. Situated at Kiara's doorstep, this public sports ground offers ample space for recreational activities.

listing_title: Expansive four-bedroom home in ideal location
listing_description:
Located in one of Griffith's most sought-after tree-lined streets, is this beautiful and expansive home. 

Enjoy the spacious living areas, including a separate open plan family room with warm timber flooring opening up to the private outdoor patio. The modern kitchen features gas cooking, a walk-in pantry and Smeg appliances, making it the home cook and entertainer's dream. 

Featuring four generous-sized bedrooms, with the master bedroom offering dual walk-in wardrobes, as well as an attached study & en-suite, all separate from the other bedrooms. The fourth bedroom located downstairs with its own access can be set up as a teenage retreat or even a home office with a built-in robe, ensuite & kitchenette.

The automatic oversize double garage has built-in storage and internal access directly into the home. 

Offering a location of absolute convenience mere minutes from Manuka, Fyshwick and the dynamic Kingston foreshore, this is the perfect opportunity to live in the sought-after area of Griffith.

Features of this home include: 

Split level home with four generous-sized bedrooms
Spacious sun-filled formal living room with built-in joinery
Open kitchen, walk-in pantry, stainless steel appliances and gas cooktop
Master bedroom suite featuring dual walk-in robes and ensuite
Separate study room located next to the main bedroom
Fourth bedroom with built-ins, ensuite, kitchenette, separate entrance
Indoor and outdoor entertainment areas
Modern bathrooms with chic fittings and quality tap-ware and bathtub 
Full-size laundry with ample storage
Timber floors and instantaneous gas hot water
